[[File:Komainu at Tozan Shrine in Arita, Saga Prefecture, made of porcelain.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|right|A ''[[komainu]]'' made of porcelain]] The {{nihongo|'''Tōzan''' or '''Sueyama Shrine'''|陶山神社}} is located in [[Arita, Saga|Arita]], [[Nishimatsuura District, Saga|Nishimatsuura District]], [[Saga Prefecture]]. The shrine has a [[porcelain]] archway and other items of porcelain which, at other shrines, are usually made of stone. This [[Shinto]] shrine was and still is particularly revered by Arita's ceramists.
The shrine was founded as Arita Sarayama Sōbyō [[Hachiman shrine|Hachimangū]] ({{lang|ja|有田皿山宗廟八幡宮}}) in 1658, and dedicated to [[Emperor Ōjin]] and [[Nabeshima Naoshige]], the latter known for known for re-settling potters from Korea in the area.<ref name="MLIT">[https://www.mlit.go.jp/tagengo-db/common/001565488.pdf "Tozan Shrine."] Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism. Retrieved 5 April 2024.</ref> In 1871, the shrine was renamed ''Sueyama-Jinja'' ({{lang|ja|陶山神社}}), literally "ceramic mountain shrine"; ''Tōzan'' is an [[Kanji#Readings|alternative reading]] of the ''kanji'' for ''Sueyama''.<ref name="MLIT"/> In 1917, a memorial to the semi-legendary potter [[Yi Sam-pyeong]] (Kanagae Sambee) was built on a hill overlooking the town of Arita to commemorate the 300th anniversary of [[Arita ware|Arita's porcelain]].<ref name="MLIT"/> [[File:Tozan Shrine 09 April 2011 01.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|The view of Arita from the Yi Sam-pyeong Monument]]
The 1888 ''[[torii]]'' (a Shinto shrine archway), uniquely constructed of porcelain,<ref name="MLIT"/> was designated a [[Tangible Cultural Properties of Japan|Tangible Cultural Property]] on 28 April 2000.
